#!/bin/bash
curl -X POST "http://localhost:8000/generate-video" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{
      "title": "My neighbor’s husband left today and it turned into a full-on daytime soap opera.",
      "type": "story",
      "story": "At first, I thought someone left their TV too loud. But then I realized the yelling was real and it was coming from outside. I peeked out my front window and saw my neighbor standing on the porch barefoot, in her pajama pants and a tank top, screaming at her husband. He was dragging a giant suitcase to his car and completely ignoring her. She was yelling things like: So you are just gonna walk out after everything. Be a man for once and say it to my face. You will regret this when she leaves you too. Yes. She. Not even ten minutes after the husband sped off, another car pulls up. A silver BMW. Out steps her sister, dressed like she just came from a casting for brunch in Beverly Hills. The neighbor storms off the porch and yells, Of course you show up now. The sister fires right back, He needed someone who listens to him for once. They start going at it, yelling, finger-pointing, my neighbor even pushes the sister shoulder at one point. And in the middle of all this, the neighbor screams, He was my husband. And you were supposed to be my sister. The sister responds in the calmest way after all the yelling, He told me you would do this, then she gets in the car and leaves. Half an hour later I hear glass clinking loudly. She is outside again, tossing empty wine bottles into her trash one by one, slowly and dramatically. She finally sat down on the curb and lit a cigarette. First time I have ever seen her smoke. No one came back. Her husband car was still gone. Her sister never returned. She closed all the blinds and it went silent. I decided to check on her that evening. Brought pasta, steak, garlic bread, and brownies. When she answered the door she looked drained, but she smiled a little when she saw the food and said, You did not have to do that. She confirmed what I had already suspected. Her husband and her sister had been seeing each other behind her back. She found out by accident, saw a message pop up on his iPad and it all unraveled from there. But then something shifted in the conversation. She said, I mean yeah, I made it really easy for him to cheat. I have not been emotionally available for months. She admitted she had already emotionally checked out of the marriage but stayed because she was not about to be the one to call it. Said she likes the upper hand in every exit. She talked for twenty straight minutes. The longer she talked, the more I realized she was not just a victim. The whole situation was messy. Every single person involved was somehow in the wrong. Before I left, she said something that stuck with me. At least I did not lose anything important. Just two people I outgrew anyway. And maybe that was her way of coping. Or maybe that is just who she is."
    }'